---
import Doc from '../layouts/Doc.astro';
import FeatureRow from '../components/FeatureRow.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import StatusPill from '../components/StatusPill.astro';
---

<Doc
  title="How Chips works — A2A handshake, bridge, learning loops"
  description="The mechanics: standard A2A handshake delivers consumer identity; the bridge fetches consent-mediated context across enterprises; five learning loops compound at two levels."
  pageLabel="HOW IT WORKS"
  eyebrow="MECHANICS · THE ACTUAL WIRES"
  heading={`From <em>standard handshake</em><br/>to <em>compounding network</em>.`}
  lede="Three things happen on every consumer interaction. None of them require the consumer agent to know Chips exists. None of them require the consumer to sign up. All of them compound."
>
  <FeatureRow number="01" label="THE HANDSHAKE" heading="Identity arrives via standard A2A. Not a Chips integration.">
    <p>
      Any A2A-compliant consumer agent passes a consumer identifier in its handshake to enterprise agents —
      that's the <code>securitySchemes</code> mechanism using OIDC delegated user authentication, plus
      standard claims (email, sub, wallet). Chips's enterprise agents read what the standard delivers and key on
      the canonical cross-runtime identifier <code>sha256(lower(trim(email)))</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>The consumer agent doesn't need to know Chips exists.</em> No Chips signup, no Chips-specific
      consumer-agent integration, no consumer-facing OIDC flow. Email hash is the only identifier that's both
      stable across consumer agents and available without any new integration.
    </p>
    <div slot="aside">
      <Callout variant="note">
        <p>
          <strong>Steps 1–5 of the handshake</strong> — Consumer agent does OIDC delegated user auth →
          attaches JWT on <code>SendMessage</code> → Chips validates against the consumer agent's JWKS →
          extracts + hashes email → looks up consumer record + Level B priors → attaches tier, profile,
          bridge state, applicable priors to the task context. Enterprise agent receives all of it on turn one.
        </p>
      </Callout>
    </div>
  </FeatureRow>

  <FeatureRow number="02" label="THE BRIDGE" heading="Consent in conversation. Audit logged. Scope vocabulary governed.">
    <p>
      When REI's enterprise agent wants to check whether Maya owns a fleece mid-layer from another outdoor
      retailer, it asks her inside the conversation: <em>"Mind if I check what you've bought at Backcountry to
      make a better recommendation? You can also tell me to always allow this for outdoor retail."</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      Maya replies in natural language. The enterprise agent — Chips-hosted, so we control prompt rendering —
      parses the structured intent and calls Chips's bridge runtime with the consent decision. <em>Bridge
      records the grant, issues scoped queries to target enterprise agents, aggregates, redacts, returns.</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      Consumer-agent SDK integration is an <em>upgrade path</em> that swaps conversational consent for native
      UI prompts and adds partner revenue share. It's not the baseline.
    </p>
    <div slot="aside">
      <div class="scopes">
        <span class="mono-tag"><StatusPill kind="emerald">loyalty-tier</StatusPill></span>
        <span class="mono-tag"><StatusPill kind="emerald">purchase-history</StatusPill></span>
        <span class="mono-tag"><StatusPill kind="emerald">behavioral-profile</StatusPill></span>
        <span class="mono-tag"><StatusPill kind="emerald">category-purchases-recent</StatusPill></span>
        <span class="mono-tag"><StatusPill kind="emerald">attested-claims</StatusPill></span>
        <span class="mono-tag"><StatusPill kind="emerald">size-profile</StatusPill></span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </FeatureRow>

  <FeatureRow number="03" label="THE LEARNING LAYER" heading="Every conversation is structured corpus.">
    <p>
      Five distinct learning loops accumulate at different timescales. Loops 1–3 (<em>Level A</em>) live at the
      enterprise — per-consumer state, per-SKU enrichment, per-enterprise policy refinement. Loops 4–5
      (<em>Level B</em>) live at Chips, aggregated across the network under differential privacy.
    </p>
    <p>
      <em>Level B is the moat that compounds.</em> An enterprise that builds its agent solo on Bedrock or
      Foundry gets Level A automatically. They get <em>none</em> of Level B. Day-1 cold-start on Chips operates
      above what a solo agent achieves at month 6 because it inherits the network's accumulated
      objection-handling patterns, intent taxonomies, conversion-by-context priors.
    </p>
    <div slot="aside">
      <Button href="/network-learning" variant="outline">Deep dive · Network learning</Button>
    </div>
  </FeatureRow>

  <FeatureRow number="04" label="THE RUNTIME" heading="A2A-native. BYO LLM. Eleven JSON-RPC methods over HTTP + SSE.">
    <p>
      The Chips-hosted A2A-compliant server agent publishes an Agent Card at
      <code>agents.chips.dev/&lt;enterprise&gt;/.well-known/agent.json</code> advertising skills, supported
      security schemes (OIDC for consumer-side, mTLS for enterprise→enterprise), task lifecycle support,
      streaming + push, and bridge-target scope vocabularies.
    </p>
    <p>
      Reasoning loop is your choice. <em>BYO LLM</em>, or take the Chips Commerce Agent baseline. Tasks progress
      through the A2A lifecycle: <code>submitted → working → input-required → auth-required → completed</code>.
      Every turn emits the structured event taxonomy that feeds both Level A and Level B.
    </p>
  </FeatureRow>

  <Callout variant="quote">
    <p>
      <strong>What's specifically different here:</strong> the consumer's session context arrives via the
      standard A2A handshake. The consumer agent's OIDC delegated auth flow already carries email or sub
      claims, signed by the consumer agent's IdP. Chips's enterprise agents read what's standard.
    </p>
    <p>
      The consumer agent doesn't authenticate to Chips, doesn't integrate a Chips library, and doesn't render
      any Chips-branded UI for this to work. They just speak A2A.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="next">
    <h3>Next</h3>
    <div class="next-grid">
      <a href="/network-learning" class="next-card">
        <span class="mono-label">DEEP DIVE</span>
        <span class="next-title">Network learning · five loops, two levels</span>
        <span class="next-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/pricing" class="next-card">
        <span class="mono-label">METERS</span>
        <span class="next-title">Pricing · five meters, one network</span>
        <span class="next-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/for-enterprises" class="next-card">
        <span class="mono-label">ENTERPRISES</span>
        <span class="next-title">Ship your agent in 4–8 hours</span>
        <span class="next-arrow">→</span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Doc>

<style>
  .scopes {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
  }
  .next {
    margin-top: 72px;
    padding-top: 56px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hair);
  }
  .next h3 {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--slate);
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .next-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1px;
    background: var(--hair);
    border: 1px solid var(--hair);
  }
  .next-card {
    background: var(--bg);
    padding: 28px 24px;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 8px;
    text-decoration: none;
    border-bottom: none;
    transition: background 150ms ease;
    position: relative;
  }
  .next-card:hover {
    background: var(--emerald-soft);
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .next-card .mono-label {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--emerald);
  }
  .next-title {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: 19px;
    line-height: 1.25;
    color: var(--ink);
    max-width: 22ch;
  }
  .next-arrow {
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 18px;
    right: 18px;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--slate);
    transition: transform 200ms ease, color 200ms ease;
  }
  .next-card:hover .next-arrow {
    transform: translateX(3px);
    color: var(--emerald);
  }
  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .next-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
</style>
